{{Economics sidebar}}
'''Sports economics''' is a discipline of [[economics]] focused on its relationship to [[sports]]. It covers both the ways in which economists can study the distinctive institutions of sports, and the ways in which sports can allow economists to research many topics, including [[discrimination]] and [[antitrust law]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780195387773.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780195387773 |title=The Oxford Handbook of Sports Economics |date=2012-04-13 |publisher=Oxford University Press |language=en |doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780195387773.001.0001}}</ref> The theoretical foundations of the discipline are heavily based on [[microeconomics]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.studyingeconomics.ac.uk/module-options/sports-economics/ |title=Sports Economics  |website=Studying Economics |language=en |access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref> As of 2006, about 100 to 120 college professors taught sports economics courses.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/2006-07-27-sports-econ-usat_x.htm |title=Batter up! Sports economics hits field |last=Kirchhoff |first=Sue |date=2006-07-27 |work=USA Today |access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref>
